Scope
The application will remain intentionally small and focused.
The system will consist of:

A WinForms user interface
Basic C# domain objects
Validation logic for reservation data
JSON file storage for persistence
Simple display of saved reservations
Users will be able to:
Enter reservation information
Submit reservations
Receive validation feedback
Save valid reservations
View previously saved reservations


Core Reservation Fields
Customer Name
Reservation Date
Party Size

Validation Rules
Customer Name is required
Reservation Date must be in the future
Party Size must be greater than zero

Duplicate reservations are not allowed
Same Customer Name
Same Reservation Date

Technical Learning Goals
Object-Oriented Programming
Classes and Properties
Collections and Lists
JSON Serialization
File Operations
Event-Driven Programming
Separation of UI and Business Logic
Debugging Techniques
QA Learning Goals
Requirement Analysis
Validation Testing
Boundary Testing
Negative Testing
Test Case Creation
Defect Reporting
Manual Testing
Introductory NUnit Automation



Out of Scope
The following features will not be included:
User accounts
Authentication
SQL databases
Networking
Cloud storage
Complex reporting
Advanced UI styling
Multi-user support
Production deployment

Success Criteria
The project is considered successful when:
Users can create reservations through the WinForms interface.
Validation rules function correctly.
Reservations are saved to a JSON file.
Reservations can be displayed from saved data.
Manual test cases are executed and documented.
Core validation rules are covered by NUnit tests.

This project exists primarily to improve C# skills and develop a structured QA problem-solving mindset.
